Cysticerosis has a worldwide distribution, mainly where pigs are consumed and sanitation is substandard (see Streptococcus suis map for pig density and Sanitation map). In endemic countries it is an important cause of epilepsy, causing a high disease burden in mainly poor families. In several countries neurocysticercosis is the cause of 10–50% of seizures. Neurocysticercosis is common in Latin America and non-Muslim African and Asian countries where pig is eaten and traditional pig rearing is practiced. Regions with the habit of eating raw or undercooked pig meat are at increased risk. In Europe, cysticercosis has largely disappeared due to strong health system and good sanitation. In several developed nations, like the USA and Spain, there is an increase in certain regions where lots of migrants live who have come from high endemic countries. Tapeworm carriers can cause small outbreaks, as was observed in a Jewish community in New York that employed cooks from Latin America.
